         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Education Office ¶ Dunedin ¶  Jany 16th  ¶ 187 ¶ 7 ¶ My Dear Baron, ¶  ¶ I have borne your request in mind, and now send you a lot of the flowers of S. grammena ¶  from Bluff &amp; Invercargill. ¶  It gro...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">78.01.16</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Donald Petrie</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M1, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS found with a specimen of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Stylidium%20subulatum">Stylidium subulatum</name>
                     </seg> (MEL 2469192). MS annotated by M: 'Answ 22/1/78'. Letter not found. </p>
               </note>
               <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times; ">Education Office</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times; ">Dunedin</seg> Jany 16th <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times; ">187</seg>7<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">The date given by M in his annotation suggests that Petrie has written the wrong year number, and the letter is therefore dated to 1878.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My Dear Baron,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have borne your request in mind, and now send you a lot of the flowers of S. grammena<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">grammena <seg style="font-style: italic; ">crossed out and</seg> subulatum <seg style="font-style: italic; ">written above in M's hand</seg>.</p>
               </note> from Bluff &amp; Invercargill.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">Both on the south coast of the South Island of New Zealand. No letter from M to Petrie requesting such flowers has been found, but see M to F. Hutton, 13 May 1877, where he requests them. In 'Observations on the genus <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Phyllachne</seg>', <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Journal of botany, British and foreign,</seg>
                     <seg style=""> vol. 16 (1878), pp. </seg>173-4 (B78.06.01), M reported that Petrie's specimens had verified his long-held belief '<seg style="">that this rare and remarkable plant would be found referable to </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Forstera</seg>
                     <seg style=""> (</seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">i.e., Phyllachne</seg>
                     <seg style="">)'.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> It grows a few feet above sea level to 800 or so on Bluff Hill. I have found it lately near Dunedin altitude 2000 feet. I have been unable to detect any irritability though I have tested the point repeatedly. I hope the specimens will answer your purpose. As mail is closing I cannot say more just now.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Yours sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>D. Petrie.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Stylidium%20subulatum">Stylidium subulatum</name>
            </p>
